%I A395156 #19 May 27 2026 16:03:04
%S A395156 3,10,21,78,55,171,136,105,351,903,666,253,465,1953,8001,820,406,595,
%T A395156 2211
%N A395156 Square array read by antidiagonals upwards: T(n,k) is the n-th number j with the property that the symmetric representation of sigma(j) has 2*k parts and two parts meet at the center of the Dyck paths, n >= 1, k >= 1, j >= 1.
%C A395156 This is a permutation of A298856 (the second hexagonal numbers without middle divisors).
%C A395156 Conjecture: T(n,k) is the n-th number j with exactly 2*k 2-dense sublists of divisors and 2*A033676(j) = A033677(j) - 1.
%e A395156 The corner of the square array begins:
%e A395156       3,   21   171,  903, ...
%e A395156      10,   55,  351, 1953, ...
%e A395156      78,  105,  465, 2211, ...
%e A395156     136,  253,  595, 3081, ...
%e A395156     666,  406,  741, 4465, ...
%e A395156     820, 1081, 1275, 5253, ...
%e A395156    1830, 1378, 2485, 6105, ...
%e A395156    2628, 1711, 2775, 7021, ...
%e A395156    4656, 2926, 3741, 8515, ...
%e A395156    5886, 3403, 5050, 9591, ...
%e A395156   ...
%e A395156 For j = 21 the 21st row of A237593 is [11, 4, 3, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 3, 4, 11] and the 20th row of A237593 is [11, 4, 2, 1, 2, 2, 1, 2, 4, 11] so we can draw the diagram of the symmetric representation of sigma(21) in the first quadrant as shown below:
%e A395156      _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _
%e A395156     |_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _|
%e A395156                           |
%e A395156                           |
%e A395156                           |_ _ _
%e A395156                           |_ _  |_
%e A395156                               |_ _|_
%e A395156                                   | |_
%e A395156                                   |_  |
%e A395156                                     | |
%e A395156                                     |_|_ _ _ _
%e A395156                                             | |
%e A395156                                             | |
%e A395156                                             | |
%e A395156                                             | |
%e A395156                                             | |
%e A395156                                             | |
%e A395156                                             | |
%e A395156                                             | |
%e A395156                                             | |
%e A395156                                             | |
%e A395156                                             |_|
%e A395156 .
%e A395156 We can see that between the two Dyck paths the diagram has four parts (or regions) and two parts meet at the center of the Dyck paths, so 21 is in the sequence, more precisely, 21 is in the second column of the square array.
%Y A395156 Row 1 gives A394791.
%Y A395156 Column 1 gives A262259.
%Y A395156 Other sequences where two parts meet at the center of the Dyck path are A191363, A262259, A264104, A298856, A392197 and A394791.
%Y A395156 Cf. A000203, A014105, A033676, A033677, A071561, A207375, A237270, A237271, A237593 (Dyck paths), A240062, A262626, A280107, A320511, A384222 (2-dense sublists).
